    ref:'1 Corinthians 10:31',
    imgQuery:'Leyte Kalanggaman sandbar aerial Philippines',
    reflection:'You\'re not actually sick, but the deadline is stressful and a day off sounds appealing, and calling in feels like a victimless shortcut since sick leave is technically \'yours\' to use. But there\'s a quiet dishonesty in claiming an illness you don\'t have, one that erodes trust even if it\'s never discovered. If you genuinely need rest, there are honest ways to ask for it — a personal day, an honest conversation about burnout. Doing everything for God\'s glory, including how you request time off, means even the paperwork you file reflects the same integrity you\'d want visible in bigger decisions. Small dishonesty rehearsed regularly becomes a character default you didn\'t intend to build.',
    takeaways:['Claiming sick leave dishonestly erodes integrity even if undetected.','Genuine need for rest deserves an honest request, not a false claim.','Small habitual dishonesty shapes character defaults over time.'],
