    reflection:'OFWs are often praised as heroes, and the praise is deserved, but heroism narratives can quietly demand you skip the weeping part and go straight to gratitude and resolve. Paul\'s instruction to weep with those who weep suggests grief is meant to be shared, not bypassed for the sake of appearing strong. If you\'ve been performing okay-ness for your family\'s sake, or your own, it might help to remember that even the early church was told weeping is a legitimate, necessary response to loss — not a failure of faith. Let the cost of your sacrifice be acknowledged, not just admired from a distance.',
    takeaways:['\'Bagong bayani\' praise doesn\'t require you to skip real grief.','Weeping with those who weep is a biblical instruction, not weakness.','Acknowledging sacrifice\'s cost is more honest than only admiring it.'],
