    ref:'Daniel 1:8',
    imgQuery:'Daranak Falls Rizal Philippines',
    reflection:'Daniel was young, far from home, and under real pressure to conform to a foreign culture\'s expectations — not unlike your own situation. His resolve wasn\'t spontaneous willpower in the moment; the text says he resolved, a decision made ahead of time, before the temptation was even served on a plate. That\'s the pattern worth borrowing: decide your convictions before you\'re in the room where compromise feels easiest. Waiting to figure out your boundaries in the heat of the moment almost always ends in compromise. Deciding in advance is what let Daniel say no with calm confidence.',
    takeaways:['Convictions decided in advance hold up better than in-the-moment willpower','Pressure to conform is real, but resolve can be prepared ahead of time','Daniel\'s confidence came from deciding before the temptation, not during it'],
    question:'What pressure to compromise do you regularly face, and have you actually decided your response in advance?',
    prayer:'Lord, like Daniel, help me resolve my convictions ahead of time so I\'m not scrambling in the moment of temptation. Amen.',
    mission:'Write down one specific boundary you\'ll hold this week regarding a recurring pressure, and decide your response before the situation arises.'
